SIMPLE: wagon
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wagon
<hw>Wag"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>wagen</ets>.
⟦root⟧136. See <er>Wain</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A wheeled carriage; a vehicle on four wheels, and
usually drawn by horses; especially, one used for carrying freight or
merchandise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the United States, light <xex>wagons</xex> are used
for the conveyance of persons and light commodities.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A freight car on a railway.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A chariot</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The Dipper, or Charles's
Wain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word and its compounds are often written with two
g's (<xex>waggon</xex>, <xex>waggonage</xex>, etc.), chiefly in England.
The forms <xex>wagon</xex>, <xex>wagonage</xex>, etc., are, however,
etymologically preferable, and in the United States are almost
universally used.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wagon boiler</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Boiler</er>, 3.</cd> -- <col><b>Wagon ceiling</b></col>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>a semicircular, or wagon-headed, arch or
ceiling; -- sometimes used also of a ceiling whose section is polygonal
instead of semicircular.</cd> -- <col><b>Wagon master</b></col>, <cd>an
officer or person in charge of one or more wagons, especially of those
used for transporting freight, as the supplies of an army, and the
like.</cd> -- <col><b>Wagon shoe</b></col>, <cd>a skid, or shoe, for
retarding the motion of a wagon wheel; a drag.</cd> -- <col><b>Wagon
vault</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>See under 1st
<er>Vault</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wagon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wagon
<hw>Wag"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wagoned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wagoning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To transport in a wagon or
wagons; <as>as, goods are <ex>wagoned</ex> from city to
city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wagon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wagon
<hw>Wag"on</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To wagon goods as a business;
<as>as, the man <ex>wagons</ex> between Philadelphia and its
suburbs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wagonage</ent>⟦br⟧
